Edge locations.

Edge locations are not regions. They do not run ee-see-two or a relational database. They are much smaller facilities, deployed in many more cities than regions are, and their only job is to terminate user connections close to the user.

Picture a handful of services living at the edge. CloudFront caches and delivers your content from the nearest edge location. Route fifty-three answers d-n-s queries from the edge. The web application firewall filters web traffic at the edge. Shield provides denial-of-service protection there. And small functions, CloudFront Functions and Lambda at edge, run code right at the edge to customize requests and responses on their way through.

The takeaway is simple. Regions are where your application and data live; edge locations are a thin, wide layer whose whole purpose is speed, getting that first hop as close to the user as possible.
